english:
  title: On Cunning
  author: Lee Gyeong-dong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    They say the marketplace teems with deceit,
    And office, some claim, requires craft.
    So the clumsy merchant shivers without coat,
    While meager salary leaves the belly hollow.
    I've tried a hundred schemes, all gone awry—
    They only multiply my troubles.

    When duties end, dusk already shrouds the road.
    I mount my horse as dawn breaks at dawn.
    Sitting idle on the veranda through the night,
    I watch the stars gleam in the eastern sky.
    All day I pore over suits and documents,
    Each one twisted with cunning and deceit.

    The autumn wind blows from ten thousand miles away,
    And day by day, my longing to return grows restless.
    This itch within me—where can I scratch it?
    Where find the fingernails of the Goddess Ma?

    Though the world changes, Nine Doubts Peak remains,
    Yet no Bao Shu walks this world to know me.
    Mistakes I've made—hard to bite away the regret,
    Errors committed—I can only gnaw my fingers.

    My three parents wait in the hall above,
    And my heart grows tighter, wound ever tighter.
    First, let wisdom preserve this body,
    Then slowly, slowly, I shall repay the sovereign's grace.
  footnotes:
    - The Goddess Ma (麻姑) in Chinese legend possessed long fingernails and was said to have scratched people's backs with supernatural healing. Here it represents an impossible solution to an unbearable internal yearning.
    - Nine Doubts Peak (九疑) refers to Mount Jiuyi, the mythical dwelling place of the sage—here representing an unchanging ideal in a corrupted world.
    - Bao Shu (鮑) is the legendary friend of Guan Zhong, symbolizing true friendship and understanding; the poet laments having no such true companion in his life.
    - The 'three parents' likely refers to biological parents and other family members deserving filial respect, heightening the poet's internal conflict between duty and despair.
